summary.seg: The manuscript is a Greek rhetorical, musical, grammatical miscellany from the 15th century.

Although the manuscript has been copied almost entirely by the same scribe (hand A), three parts can be distinguished,on the basis of the original numbering of quires and of the type of paper which was used.

foliation.p: Early modern foliation in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right; two endleaves are unnumbered (ff. [i], [ii]); in the numbering, 180 is missing (without loss of a leaf), and 221 is repeated twice (ff. 221, 221[a]): [i] + 1-179, 181-221, 221[a], 222-326 + [ii].

collation.signatures: Modern, Greek signatures in pencil, on the lower corner, right, of the first recto of the quires, from γ΄ (3, f. 25r), to μ΄ (40, f. 319r).

condition.p: The manuscript is in fair condition. The leaves are yellowed and stained, but the text is always readable.

additions.p: On f. [i] recto the shelfmark is written in black ink Gg-1-2.
On f. [i] verso there is a title in French, written in a grey ink by a hand recurring in the manuscripts owned by J.-B. Hautin (see History).

binding.p:
Modern western binding. Paper and bookcloth (on the spine) cover over couched-laminate boards. Gold tooling on spine with shelfmark Gg.I.2 and title Graeca.
230 153 55
binding.condition: The cover is stained and worn.

accMat.p: On f. [i] verso has been pasted a small paper leaf ( 210 95 ) containing an index written in light brown ink by a hand recurring in the manuscripts owned by J.-B. Hautin, writing that name and the manuscripts' content. In this codex this hand wrote also a title on f. [i] verso, Recueil de | plusieurs autheurs grecs. The index has been implemented by at least another hand, which also added folio numbers.

Another fragment of a paper leaf is loose between ff. 128v and 129r containing a list of Greek words with numbers, perhaps part of an index, in the same ink and hand. The verso contains part of a text in French.

provenance.p: This manuscript, like many others in the CUL collection, was owned by a certain J.-B. Hautin, probably to be identified with Jean Baptiste II Hautin, son of the French scholar and numismatist Haultin, Jean-Baptiste, approximately 1580-1640 Jean-Baptiste Hautin (approximately 1580-1640) (on this matter see Jackson 2006, pp. 38-40 with bibliography; on this manuscript see p. 33 in particular). On f. [i] verso has been pasted a paper sheet with an index written by a hand recurring in the manuscripts owned by J.-B. Hautin; moreover the same hand wrote a title on f. [i] verso.

The manuscript was later owned by John Moore (1646-1714) Moore, John, 1646-1714 , bishop of Ely: number 1047 in the concordance of Bernard / Tanner numbers with the new Library classmarks, with 'Alia Addenda', compiled by F.S. Parris and Stephen Whisson in 1753, now MS Oo.7.56.

history.acquisition:
Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I
George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . On f. [i] recto is pasted the engraved bookplate made by John Pine for the Royal Library (1737).

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws partly on: A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 3: Gg-Kk, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1858, pp. 8-14.

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

support.material:
ff.1-72 Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermarks: ff. 1-24 Gothic letter L/R
with a Latin cross ( ca. 20 ca. 25 ) in the gutter, not clearly discernible.
ff. 25-31 Crescent surmounted by two horses' heads, ( ca. 45 52 ) in the gutter, no precise parallels found in the main repertoires. This type of watermark is datable to the 15th c.
ff. 32-43 Anvil surmounted by a Latin cross, in the gutter ( ca. 55 35 ) in the gutter, no precise parallels found in the main repertoires. This type of watermark is datable in the 15th c.
ff. 44-51 Footprint, in the gutter ( ca. 35 10 ) in the gutter, comparable to Wasserzeichen des Mittelalters Schuh/Schuhsohle WZMA AT8500-5125_440 , which is dated to the 3rd/4th decade of the 15th c.
ff. 52-68 Cloverleaf, with stem ( ca. 50 40 ) in the gutter, comparable to Briquet Fleur no. 6306 , which is dated to 1438/1455.
ff. 70-71 Horn, with stem ( ca. 55 80 ) in the gutter, no exact parallels were found in the main repertoires.

collation.p: The quires are mainly quaternions. The last leaf of the fourth quire is missing without loss of text.
collation.signatures:
Three Greek signatures, original to the production of the manuscript, in brown ink, in the lower margin, right:
α΄ (1) on f. 1r
α΄ (1) on f. 9r
β΄ (2) on f. 17r.

supportDesc.condition: The leaves are yellowed and stained by humidity and water. There are also brown stains. Damages on ff. 23-24 have been repaired by pasting on small paper strips. Paper strips have been glued along the upper edge of ff. 25-28, 31, probably in order to adapt them to the dimension of the other leaves.

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 1r-16r A single column of 21 lines. 140 80
ff. 19r-70v A single column of 27-30 lines. 155-160 80-90

handNote.p: ff. 1r-17v l. 2, 19r-19v, 20v-30v, 31v-70v Hand A: minuscule script slanting to the right, characterized by a strong emphasis in tracing oblique strokes, rather regular in size, with the exception of some enlarged letters, such as phi, omicron, alpha, and ligatures, such as epsilon-csi, epsilon-ypsilon, the compendium for καὶ. From f. 19r the script becomes smaller, the differences in the size of letters become less evident, as well as the emphasis on the oblique strokes. The script appears less regular and more nervous, but its charatcteristic forms are still recognizable, such as majuscule beta with irregular lobes, the lower going under the line, zeta in form of a '2', high tau in a 'flag'-form.
The text is written in a brown ink, titles and initials in red. Sometimes round parts of letters are filled with red ink.
ff. 17v l. 3-18v, 20r Hand B: the texts with musical notations in these leaves were written by another, probably contemporary hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. 1r there is a rectangular headpiece filled with branches and scrolls, coloured in red.
Small flourishings, rinceaux in red ink are traced near some titles, see e.g. ff. 64v-65r.
Initials in ekthesis, in red ink, are decorated with a simple vegetal motif, see e.g. f. 1r.
There are also smaller thick initials in ekthesis in red ink, see e.g. f. 2v.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript, on the basis of the script and of the watermarks, can be dated in the 15th c., probably around the middle of the century.

support.material:
ff. 73-302 Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermarks: ff. 73-136 Mountain in a circle ( ca. 30 ca. 30 ) in the gutter, comparable to Harlfinger Monts 71, 72, 77, 78, which are dated to 1431, 1439 and 1440, 1442, 1445.
ff. 137-144 Letter R ( ca. 35 ca. 25 ) (but it is not completely visible) in the gutter, comparable to Harlfinger Lettre 34, 37, which are dated to 1407/8, 1431.
ff. 145-160 Mountain possibly surmounted by a Latin cross, ( ca. 20 ca.25 ) in the gutter, the watermark is not entirely visible due to its position, it is nevertheless comparable to the type Harlfinger Monts 17, 25ab, 27, 43, 44, which are dated to 1431, 1435/1437, 1442, 1455, 1461.
ff. 161-193 Crescent, in a circle ( ca. 35 ca. 40 ) in the gutter, comparable to the type Briquet Croissant 5198 , which is dated to 1413 and 1431.
ff. 194-248, 281-294 Anvil ( ca. 25 ca. 30 ) in the gutter, it is the same watermark which recurs in ff. 303-326, no precise parallels were found in the main repertoires.
ff. 249-250, 255-256 Crown, under it monogram ( ca. 30 25 ) in the gutter, similar to Harlfinger Couronne 31 , which is dated to 1463.
ff. 251-254 Bull's head, with nostrils and eyes, surmounted by letter S
( ca. 55 28 ) in the gutter, no precise parallels were found in the main repertoires.
ff. 257-264 Cloverleaf, with stem ( ca. 50 40 ) in the gutter, comparable to Briquet Fleur 6306 , which is dated to 1438/1455, and to Harlfinger Fleur 80 , which is dated to 1446.
ff. 265-280 Footprint ( ca. 30 10 ) in the gutter, comparable to Harlfinger Semelle de soulier 11 , which is dated to 1435/1437.
ff. 295- Two crossed arrows ( ca. 55 32 ) in the gutter, comparable to Harlfinger Flèche 12 , which is dated to 1468.

collation.signatures:
Greek signatures, original to the production of the manuscript, in brown ink, are visible throughout in the upper or lower margin, right, of the first leaf recto of the quire, and in the lower margin, right, of the last verso:
ζ΄ (7) on f. 121r
ια΄ (11) on f. 153r
ιβ΄ (12) on f. 161r
ιγ΄ (13) on f. 169r
ιδ΄ (14) on f. 177r
ιϛ΄ (16) on ff. f. 194r and 201v
ιζ΄ (17) on ff. 202r and 209v
ιη΄ (18) on ff. 210r and 217v
ιθ΄ (19) on ff. 218r and 224v
κ΄ (20) on ff. 225r and 232v
κα΄ (21) on ff. 233r and 240v
κβ΄ (22) on ff. 241r and 248v
κγ΄ (23) on ff. 265r and 272v
κδ΄ (24) on ff. 273r and 280v
κε΄ (25) on ff. 281r and 288v
κϛ΄ (26) on f. 289r
μβ΄ (42) on ff. 295r and 302v
The series of signatures shows that quires 32 (ff. 249-256) and 33 (257-264), which are now unnumbered and placed between quire 31 (ff. 241-248), with signature κβ΄ (22) and quire 34 (ff. 265-272), with signature κγ΄ (23), seem to have been inserted there after the origial signatures were written. The last quire of this part, quire 38 (ff. 295-302), with signature μβ΄ (42), comes after quire 37 (ff. 289-294), with signature κϛ΄ (26).

handNote.p: The text is written in a brown ink, titles and initials in red. Sometimes round parts of letters are filled with red ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. 73r there is a rectangular headpiece filled with branches and scrolls, and 6 wheels, coloured in a now faded red ink.
A small linear frieze in brown ink with clovers at both ends is used as line-filler to signal the beginning of the part dedicated to the masculine names, f. 91r.
Small flourishings, rinceaux in red ink are traced near some titles, see e.g. ff. f. 129r, 136v, f. 179r, f. 249r.
Initials in ekthesis, in red ink, decorated with a simple vegetal motif, see e.g. f. 136v.
There are also smaller thick initials in ekthesis in red ink, see e.g. f. 73r.

accMat.p:
In the manuscript is preserved a loose small paper leaf (here f. [228a]; western paper, no watermark is visible,
170 90 ) with a list of words in Greek, beginning with α and β, accompanied by an Arabic number: it is probably the beginning of an alphabetical index, it does not seem to refer to this manuscript; it was probably written by a western European hand. On the verso there are traces of script, in Latin.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript, on the basis of the script and of the watermarks, can be dated to the 15th century., probably around the middle of the century.
